  "text": "Several other nuclear proteins were also recently identified to be involved in NF-κB signaling regulation in the nucleus, such as the protein kinase A-interacting protein 1 (AKIP1) [CITATION_1] and the CHFR protein, encoded by checkpoint with forkhead and ring finger domains gene [CITATION_2] (Table 1) . AKIP1 was revealed to retain p65 in the nucleus and recruit the catalytic subunit of PKA (PKAc) to phosphorylate p65. Therefore, AKIP1 augments NF-κB transactivation by dramatically enhancing the assembly of p65 with the CBP/p300 coactivator and subsequent binding of NF-κB to target DNA. In contrast, CHFR was shown to physically interact with p65 and antagonize the transcriptional activity of p65 [CITATION_3] . Although the precise mechanism by which CHFR attenuates p65 transcriptional activity still needs further definition, a functional relationship between CHFR-regulated IL-8 expression in human cancer cells and inflammation/angiogenesis was discerned in a xenograft model.",
